#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:3
msgid "Spinning Up as a Deep RL Researcher"
msgstr "成為深度強化學習 (Deep RL) 研究者"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:4
msgid "By Joshua Achiam, October 13th, 2018"
msgstr "作者：Joshua Achiam，2018 年 10 月 13 日"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:8
msgid "Table of Contents"
msgstr "目錄"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:10
msgid ""
"If you're an aspiring deep RL researcher, you've probably heard all kinds"
" of things about deep RL by this point. You know that `it's hard and it "
"doesn't always work`_. That even when you're following a recipe, "
"`reproducibility`_ `is a challenge`_. And that if you're starting from "
"scratch, `the learning curve is incredibly steep`_. It's also the case "
"that there are a lot of `great`_ `resources`_ `out`_ `there`_, but the "
"material is new enough that there's not a clear, well-charted path to "
"mastery. The goal of this column is to help you get past the initial "
"hurdle, and give you a clear sense of how to spin up as a deep RL "
"researcher. In particular, this will outline a useful curriculum for "
"increasing raw knowledge, while interleaving it with the odds and ends "
"that lead to better research."
msgstr ""
"如果你是一位有抱負的深度 RL 研究者，到目前為止你可能已經聽過各種關於深度 RL "
"的說法。你知道 `it's hard and it doesn't always work`_。即使你在遵循一個方法，"
"`reproducibility`_ `is a challenge`_。而且如果你從零開始，"
"`the learning curve is incredibly steep`_。此外，確實有很多 `great`_ "
"`resources`_ `out`_ `there`_，但這些材料足夠新，以至於目前還沒有一條清晰、"
"完善的精通之路。本文的目標是幫助你克服最初的障礙，讓你清楚地了解如何成為"
"深度 RL 研究者。特別是，這將概述一個有用的學習課程來增加基礎知識，同時穿插"
"一些能促進更好研究的零散要點。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:14
msgid "The Right Background"
msgstr "合適的背景知識"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:16
msgid ""
"**Build up a solid mathematical background.** From probability and "
"statistics, feel comfortable with random variables, Bayes' theorem, chain"
" rule of probability, expected values, standard deviations, and "
"importance sampling. From multivariate calculus, understand gradients and"
" (optionally, but it'll help) Taylor series expansions."
msgstr ""
"**建立扎實的數學基礎。** 在機率與統計方面，要熟悉隨機變數、貝氏定理、"
"機率鏈式法則、期望值、標準差和重要性採樣 (Importance Sampling)。"
"在多變量微積分方面，要理解梯度以及（可選但有幫助的）泰勒級數展開。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:18
msgid ""
"**Build up a general knowledge of deep learning.** You don't need to know"
" every single special trick and architecture, but the basics help. Know "
"about standard architectures (`MLP`_, `vanilla RNN`_, `LSTM`_ (`also see "
"this blog`_), `GRU`_, `conv`_ `layers`_, `resnets`_, `attention`_ "
"`mechanisms`_), common regularizers (`weight decay`_, `dropout`_), "
"normalization (`batch norm`_, `layer norm`_, `weight norm`_), and "
"optimizers (`SGD, momentum SGD`_, `Adam`_, `others`_). Know what the "
"`reparameterization trick`_ is."
msgstr ""
"**建立深度學習的通識知識。** 你不需要知道每一個特殊技巧和架構，但基礎知識"
"是有幫助的。了解標準架構（`MLP`_、`vanilla RNN`_、`LSTM`_（`also see "
"this blog`_）、`GRU`_、`conv`_ `layers`_、`resnets`_、`attention`_ "
"`mechanisms`_）、常見正則化器（`weight decay`_、`dropout`_）、"
"正規化（`batch norm`_、`layer norm`_、`weight norm`_）以及"
"優化器（`SGD, momentum SGD`_、`Adam`_、`others`_）。了解什麼是 "
"`reparameterization trick`_。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:20
msgid ""
"**Become familiar with at least one deep learning library.** "
"`Tensorflow`_ or `PyTorch`_ would be a good place to start. You don't "
"need to know how to do everything, but you should feel pretty confident "
"in implementing a simple program to do supervised learning."
msgstr ""
"**至少熟悉一個深度學習框架。** `Tensorflow`_ 或 `PyTorch`_ 是不錯的入門選擇。"
"你不需要知道如何做所有事情，但你應該有信心實作一個簡單的監督式學習 "
"(Supervised Learning) 程式。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:22
msgid ""
"**Get comfortable with the main concepts and terminology in RL.** Know "
"what states, actions, trajectories, policies, rewards, value functions, "
"and action-value functions are. If you're unfamiliar, Spinning Up ships "
"with `an introduction`_ to this material; it's also worth checking out "
"the `RL-Intro`_ from the OpenAI Hackathon, or the exceptional and "
"thorough `overview by Lilian Weng`_. Optionally, if you're the sort of "
"person who enjoys mathematical theory, study up on the math of `monotonic"
" improvement theory`_ (which forms the basis for advanced policy gradient"
" algorithms), or `classical RL algorithms`_ (which despite being "
"superseded by deep RL algorithms, contain valuable insights that "
"sometimes drive new research)."
msgstr ""
"**熟悉 RL 的主要概念和術語。** 了解什麼是狀態 (State)、動作 (Action)、"
"軌跡 (Trajectory)、策略 (Policy)、獎勵 (Reward)、價值函數 (Value Function) "
"和動作價值函數 (Action-Value Function)。如果你不熟悉這些，Spinning Up 附帶了 "
"`an introduction`_ 介紹這些內容；也值得查看來自 OpenAI Hackathon 的 "
"`RL-Intro`_，或 `overview by Lilian Weng`_ 這篇出色且全面的概述。"
"如果你是那種喜歡數學理論的人，可以選擇性地研究 `monotonic"
" improvement theory`_（它構成了進階策略梯度 (Policy Gradient) 演算法的基礎）"
"的數學，或 `classical RL algorithms`_（儘管已被深度 RL 演算法超越，"
"但包含有時能推動新研究的寶貴見解）。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:25
msgid "Learn by Doing"
msgstr "從實踐中學習"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:27
msgid ""
"**Write your own implementations.** You should implement as many of the "
"core deep RL algorithms from scratch as you can, with the aim of writing "
"the shortest correct implementation of each. This is by far the best way "
"to develop an understanding of how they work, as well as intuitions for "
"their specific performance characteristics."
msgstr ""
"**自己動手寫實作。** 你應該盡可能多地從頭實作核心深度 RL 演算法，目標是為"
"每個演算法撰寫最簡短且正確的實作。這是目前最好的方式來深入理解它們的"
"工作原理，以及培養對其特定效能特性的直覺。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:29
msgid ""
"**Simplicity is critical.** You should organize your efforts so that you "
"implement the simplest algorithms first, and only gradually introduce "
"complexity. If you start off trying to build something with too many "
"moving parts, odds are good that it will break and you'll lose weeks "
"trying to debug it. This is a common failure mode for people who are new "
"to deep RL, and if you find yourself stuck in it, don't be discouraged---"
"but do try to change tack and work on a simpler algorithm instead, before"
" returning to the more complex thing later."
msgstr ""
"**簡單性至關重要。** 你應該組織你的努力，先實作最簡單的演算法，然後逐步引入"
"複雜性。如果你一開始就嘗試建構包含太多活動部件的東西，很可能會出錯，"
"而你會花費數週時間來除錯。這是深度 RL 新手常見的失敗模式，如果你發現自己"
"陷入其中，不要氣餒——但確實應該嘗試改變策略，先去做一個更簡單的演算法，"
"之後再回到更複雜的東西。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:31
msgid ""
"**Which algorithms?** You should probably start with vanilla policy "
"gradient (also called `REINFORCE`_), `DQN`_, `A2C`_ (the synchronous "
"version of `A3C`_), `PPO`_ (the variant with the clipped objective), and "
"`DDPG`_, approximately in that order. The simplest versions of all of "
"these can be written in just a few hundred lines of code (ballpark "
"250-300), and some of them even less (for example, `a no-frills version "
"of VPG`_ can be written in about 80 lines). Write single-threaded code "
"before you try writing parallelized versions of these algorithms. (Do try"
" to parallelize at least one.)"
msgstr ""
"**該學哪些演算法？** 你應該從普通策略梯度（也稱為 `REINFORCE`_）開始，"
"然後依次是 `DQN`_、`A2C`_（`A3C`_ 的同步版本）、`PPO`_（帶截斷目標函數的"
"變體）和 `DDPG`_，大致按這個順序。所有這些的最簡版本都可以用幾百行程式碼"
"寫出來（大約 250-300 行），其中一些甚至更少（例如，`a no-frills version "
"of VPG`_ 可以用大約 80 行寫出來）。先寫單執行緒程式碼，然後再嘗試寫這些"
"演算法的平行化版本。（一定要嘗試平行化至少一個。）"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:33
msgid ""
"**Focus on understanding.** Writing working RL code requires clear, "
"detail-oriented understanding of the algorithms. This is because **broken"
" RL code almost always fails silently,** where the code appears to run "
"fine except that the agent never learns how to solve the task. Usually "
"the problem is that something is being calculated with the wrong "
"equation, or on the wrong distribution, or data is being piped into the "
"wrong place. Sometimes the only way to find these bugs is to read the "
"code with a critical eye, know exactly what it should be doing, and find "
"where it deviates from the correct behavior. Developing that knowledge "
"requires you to engage with both academic literature and other existing "
"implementations (when possible), so a good amount of your time should be "
"spent on that reading."
msgstr ""
"**專注於理解。** 要寫出可運作的 RL 程式碼，需要對演算法有清晰、注重細節的理解。"
"這是因為**有缺陷的 RL 程式碼幾乎總是靜默失敗，**程式碼看起來運行正常，"
"只是智能體 (Agent) 永遠學不會如何解決任務。通常問題出在某些東西用了錯誤的"
"方程式計算，或在錯誤的分佈上計算，或資料被導入了錯誤的地方。有時找到這些"
"錯誤的唯一方法是用挑剔的眼光閱讀程式碼，確切知道它應該做什麼，然後找到"
"它偏離正確行為的地方。培養這種知識需要你同時接觸學術文獻和其他現有的實作"
"（在可能的情況下），因此你應該花大量時間在閱讀上。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:35
msgid ""
"**What to look for in papers:** When implementing an algorithm based on a"
" paper, scour that paper, especially the ablation analyses and "
"supplementary material (where available). The ablations will give you an "
"intuition for what parameters or subroutines have the biggest impact on "
"getting things to work, which will help you diagnose bugs. Supplementary "
"material will often give information about specific details like network "
"architecture and optimization hyperparameters, and you should try to "
"align your implementation to these details to improve your chances of "
"getting it working."
msgstr ""
"**論文中該注意什麼：** 當根據一篇論文來實作演算法時，要仔細研讀那篇論文，"
"特別是消融分析 (Ablation Analysis) 和補充材料（如有）。消融分析會給你一種"
"直覺，了解哪些參數或子程序對使事情運作影響最大，這將幫助你診斷錯誤。"
"補充材料通常會提供關於特定細節的資訊，如網路架構和優化超參數 "
"(Hyperparameters)，你應該盡量使你的實作與這些細節對齊，以提高成功的機會。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:37
msgid ""
"**But don't overfit to paper details.** Sometimes, the paper prescribes "
"the use of more tricks than are strictly necessary, so be a bit wary of "
"this, and try out simplifications where possible. For example, the "
"original DDPG paper suggests a complex neural network architecture and "
"initialization scheme, as well as batch normalization. These aren't "
"strictly necessary, and some of the best-reported results for DDPG use "
"simpler networks. As another example, the original A3C paper uses "
"asynchronous updates from the various actor-learners, but it turns out "
"that synchronous updates work about as well."
msgstr ""
"**但不要過度擬合論文細節。** 有時，論文會使用比嚴格必要更多的技巧，"
"所以對此要有所警覺，在可能的情況下嘗試簡化。例如，原始 DDPG 論文建議使用"
"複雜的神經網路架構和初始化方案，以及批次正規化 (Batch Normalization)。"
"這些並非嚴格必要，而且 DDPG 一些最佳報告結果使用的是更簡單的網路。"
"另一個例子是，原始 A3C 論文使用來自各個 actor-learner 的非同步更新，"
"但事實證明同步更新的效果差不多。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:39
msgid ""
"**Don't overfit to existing implementations either.** Study `existing`_ "
"`implementations`_ for inspiration, but be careful not to overfit to the "
"engineering details of those implementations. RL libraries frequently "
"make choices for abstraction that are good for code reuse between "
"algorithms, but which are unnecessary if you're only writing a single "
"algorithm or supporting a single use case."
msgstr ""
"**也不要過度擬合現有實作。** 研讀 `existing`_ `implementations`_ 以獲取靈感，"
"但注意不要過度擬合那些實作的工程細節。RL 函式庫經常做出有利於演算法之間"
"程式碼重用的抽象選擇，但如果你只是寫一個演算法或支援一個使用案例，"
"這些是不必要的。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:41
msgid ""
"**Iterate fast in simple environments.** To debug your implementations, "
"try them with simple environments where learning should happen quickly, "
"like CartPole-v0, InvertedPendulum-v0, FrozenLake-v0, and HalfCheetah-v2 "
"(with a short time horizon---only 100 or 250 steps instead of the full "
"1000) from the `OpenAI Gym`_. Don't try to run an algorithm in Atari or a"
" complex Humanoid environment if you haven't first verified that it works"
" on the simplest possible toy task. Your ideal experiment turnaround-time"
" at the debug stage is <5 minutes (on your local machine) or slightly "
"longer but not much. These small-scale experiments don't require any "
"special hardware, and can be run without too much trouble on CPUs."
msgstr ""
"**在簡單環境中快速迭代。** 為了除錯你的實作，在學習應該很快發生的簡單環境中"
"測試它們，如 `OpenAI Gym`_ 中的 CartPole-v0、InvertedPendulum-v0、"
"FrozenLake-v0 和 HalfCheetah-v2（使用較短的時間範圍——只有 100 或 250 步"
"而不是完整的 1000 步）。如果你還沒有在最簡單的玩具任務上驗證演算法有效，"
"就不要嘗試在 Atari 或複雜的 Humanoid 環境中運行它。你在除錯階段理想的"
"實驗週轉時間是 <5 分鐘（在本地機器上）或稍長但不要太久。這些小規模實驗"
"不需要任何特殊硬體，可以在 CPU 上順利運行。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:43
msgid ""
"**If it doesn't work, assume there's a bug.** Spend a lot of effort "
"searching for bugs before you resort to tweaking hyperparameters: usually"
" it's a bug. Bad hyperparameters can significantly degrade RL "
"performance, but if you're using hyperparameters similar to the ones in "
"papers and standard implementations, those will probably not be the "
"issue. Also worth keeping in mind: sometimes things will work in one "
"environment even when you have a breaking bug, so make sure to test in "
"more than one environment once your results look promising."
msgstr ""
"**如果不能運作，假設有錯誤。** 在調整超參數之前，花大量精力尋找錯誤："
"通常是個 bug。不好的超參數確實會顯著降低 RL 效能，但如果你使用的超參數"
"與論文和標準實作中的類似，那些可能不是問題所在。另外值得記住的是："
"有時即使你有一個致命的 bug，某些東西在一個環境中仍然能運作，所以一旦"
"你的結果看起來有希望，確保在多個環境中測試。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:45
msgid ""
"**Measure everything.** Do a lot of instrumenting to see what's going on "
"under-the-hood. The more stats about the learning process you read out at"
" each iteration, the easier it is to debug---after all, you can't tell "
"it's broken if you can't see that it's breaking. I personally like to "
"look at the mean/std/min/max for cumulative rewards, episode lengths, and"
" value function estimates, along with the losses for the objectives, and "
"the details of any exploration parameters (like mean entropy for "
"stochastic policy optimization, or current epsilon for epsilon-greedy as "
"in DQN). Also, watch videos of your agent's performance every now and "
"then; this will give you some insights you wouldn't get otherwise."
msgstr ""
"**測量一切。** 做大量的監測來了解底層發生的事情。你在每次迭代中讀取的"
"學習過程統計資訊越多，除錯就越容易——畢竟，如果你看不到它在出問題，"
"就無法判斷它是否出了問題。我個人喜歡查看累積獎勵 (Cumulative Rewards)、"
"回合長度和價值函數估計的均值/標準差/最小值/最大值，以及目標函數的損失值，"
"還有任何探索 (Exploration) 參數的細節（如隨機策略優化的平均熵，或 DQN 中 "
"epsilon-greedy 的當前 epsilon）。此外，時不時觀看智能體表現的影片；"
"這會給你一些其他方式無法獲得的洞察。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:47
msgid ""
"**Scale experiments when things work.** After you have an implementation "
"of an RL algorithm that seems to work correctly in the simplest "
"environments, test it out on harder environments. Experiments at this "
"stage will take longer---on the order of somewhere between a few hours "
"and a couple of days, depending. Specialized hardware---like a beefy GPU "
"or a 32-core machine---might be useful at this point, and you should "
"consider looking into cloud computing resources like AWS or GCE."
msgstr ""
"**當有效果時擴大實驗規模。** 在你的 RL 演算法實作在最簡單的環境中似乎正確"
"運作之後，在更困難的環境中測試它。這個階段的實驗會花更長時間——大約在"
"幾小時到幾天之間，視情況而定。專用硬體——如強大的 GPU 或 32 核心的機器——"
"在這個階段可能會很有用，你應該考慮研究雲端運算資源，如 AWS 或 GCE。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:49
msgid ""
"**Keep these habits!** These habits are worth keeping beyond the stage "
"where you're just learning about deep RL---they will accelerate your "
"research!"
msgstr ""
"**保持這些習慣！** 這些習慣值得在你僅僅學習深度 RL 的階段之後繼續保持——"
"它們會加速你的研究！"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:52
msgid "Developing a Research Project"
msgstr "發展研究專案"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:54
msgid ""
"Once you feel reasonably comfortable with the basics in deep RL, you "
"should start pushing on the boundaries and doing research. To get there, "
"you'll need an idea for a project."
msgstr ""
"一旦你對深度 RL 的基礎感到相當自在，你就應該開始突破邊界並進行研究。"
"為了達到那個目標，你需要一個專案的想法。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:56
msgid ""
"**Start by exploring the literature to become aware of topics in the "
"field.** There are a wide range of topics you might find interesting: "
"sample efficiency, exploration, transfer learning, hierarchy, memory, "
"model-based RL, meta learning, and multi-agent, to name a few. If you're "
"looking for inspiration, or just want to get a rough sense of what's out "
"there, check out Spinning Up's `key papers "
"<../spinningup/keypapers.html>`_ list. Find a paper that you enjoy on one"
" of these subjects---something that inspires you---and read it "
"thoroughly. Use the related work section and citations to find closely-"
"related papers and do a deep dive in the literature. You'll start to "
"figure out where the unsolved problems are and where you can make an "
"impact."
msgstr ""
"**從探索文獻開始，了解該領域的主題。** 你可能會發現很多有趣的主題："
"樣本效率 (Sample Efficiency)、探索 (Exploration)、遷移學習 "
"(Transfer Learning)、層級式學習 (Hierarchy)、記憶 (Memory)、"
"基於模型的 RL (Model-Based RL)、元學習 (Meta Learning) 和多智能體 "
"(Multi-Agent)，僅舉幾例。如果你在尋找靈感，或只是想大致了解有什麼，"
"可以查看 Spinning Up 的 `key papers <../spinningup/keypapers.html>`_ 列表。"
"找一篇你在這些主題之一上喜歡的論文——某種能啟發你的東西——並徹底閱讀它。"
"利用相關工作部分和引用來找到密切相關的論文，並深入研究文獻。你會開始弄清楚"
"未解決的問題在哪裡，以及你可以在哪裡產生影響。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:58
msgid ""
"**Approaches to idea-generation:** There are a many different ways to "
"start thinking about ideas for projects, and the frame you choose "
"influences how the project might evolve and what risks it will face. Here"
" are a few examples:"
msgstr ""
"**產生想法的方法：** 有很多不同的方式來開始思考專案的想法，你選擇的框架"
"會影響專案的發展方向和它將面臨的風險。以下是一些例子："

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:60
msgid ""
"**Frame 1: Improving on an Existing Approach.** This is the "
"incrementalist angle, where you try to get performance gains in an "
"established problem setting by tweaking an existing algorithm. "
"Reimplementing prior work is super helpful here, because it exposes you "
"to the ways that existing algorithms are brittle and could be improved. A"
" novice will find this the most accessible frame, but it can also be "
"worthwhile for researchers at any level of experience. While some "
"researchers find incrementalism less exciting, some of the most "
"impressive achievements in machine learning have come from work of this "
"nature."
msgstr ""
"**框架一：改進現有方法。** 這是漸進主義的角度，你嘗試在既定的問題設定中"
"透過調整現有演算法來獲得效能提升。在這裡重新實作先前的工作非常有幫助，"
"因為它讓你接觸到現有演算法的脆弱之處以及可以改進的地方。新手會覺得這個"
"框架最容易上手，但對任何經驗層級的研究者來說也是值得的。雖然一些研究者"
"覺得漸進主義不夠令人興奮，但機器學習中一些最令人印象深刻的成就正是來自"
"這類工作。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:62
msgid ""
"Because projects like these are tied to existing methods, they are by "
"nature narrowly scoped and can wrap up quickly (a few months), which may "
"be desirable (especially when starting out as a researcher). But this "
"also sets up the risks: it's possible that the tweaks you have in mind "
"for an algorithm may fail to improve it, in which case, unless you come "
"up with more tweaks, the project is just over and you have no clear "
"signal on what to do next."
msgstr ""
"因為這類專案與現有方法綁定，它們本質上範圍較窄，可以快速完成（幾個月），"
"這可能是可取的（特別是作為研究者剛起步時）。但這也帶來了風險：你對演算法"
"的調整可能無法改善它，在這種情況下，除非你想出更多的調整方案，否則專案"
"就結束了，你也沒有明確的下一步方向。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:64
msgid ""
"**Frame 2: Focusing on Unsolved Benchmarks.** Instead of thinking about "
"how to improve an existing method, you aim to succeed on a task that no "
"one has solved before. For example: achieving perfect generalization from"
" training levels to test levels in the `Sonic domain`_ or `Gym Retro`_. "
"When you hammer away at an unsolved task, you might try a wide variety of"
" methods, including prior approaches and new ones that you invent for the"
" project. It is possible for a novice to approch this kind of problem, "
"but there will be a steeper learning curve."
msgstr ""
"**框架二：專注於未解決的基準測試。** 不是考慮如何改進現有方法，而是以在"
"尚未有人解決的任務上取得成功為目標。例如：在 `Sonic domain`_ 或 "
"`Gym Retro`_ 中實現從訓練關卡到測試關卡的完美泛化 (Generalization)。"
"當你在一個未解決的任務上持續努力時，你可能會嘗試各種方法，包括先前的方法"
"和你為專案發明的新方法。新手也可以嘗試這類問題，但學習曲線會更陡峭。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:66
msgid ""
"Projects in this frame have a broad scope and can go on for a while "
"(several months to a year-plus). The main risk is that the benchmark is "
"unsolvable without a substantial breakthrough, meaning that it would be "
"easy to spend a lot of time without making any progress on it. But even "
"if a project like this fails, it often leads the researcher to many new "
"insights that become fertile soil for the next project."
msgstr ""
"這個框架下的專案範圍廣泛，可能會持續很長時間（幾個月到一年以上）。"
"主要風險是基準測試在沒有重大突破的情況下可能無法解決，這意味著你可能會"
"花很多時間而沒有任何進展。但即使這類專案失敗了，它通常會引導研究者獲得"
"許多新的洞察，這些洞察會成為下一個專案的肥沃土壤。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:69
msgid ""
"**Frame 3: Create a New Problem Setting.** Instead of thinking about "
"existing methods or current grand challenges, think of an entirely "
"different conceptual problem that hasn't been studied yet. Then, figure "
"out how to make progress on it. For projects along these lines, a "
"standard benchmark probably doesn't exist yet, and you will have to "
"design one. This can be a huge challenge, but it's worth embracing---"
"great benchmarks move the whole field forward."
msgstr ""
"**框架三：創造新的問題設定。** 不是考慮現有方法或當前的重大挑戰，而是想"
"一個尚未被研究過的全新概念性問題。然後，找出如何在這個問題上取得進展。"
"對於這類專案，標準基準測試可能還不存在，你將不得不設計一個。這可能是一個"
"巨大的挑戰，但值得擁抱——優秀的基準測試能推動整個領域前進。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:71
msgid ""
"Problems in this frame come up when they come up---it's hard to go "
"looking for them."
msgstr ""
"這個框架下的問題在出現時才會出現——很難刻意去尋找它們。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:73
msgid ""
"**Avoid reinventing the wheel.** When you come up with a good idea that "
"you want to start testing, that's great! But while you're still in the "
"early stages with it, do the most thorough check you can to make sure it "
"hasn't already been done. It can be pretty disheartening to get halfway "
"through a project, and only then discover that there's already a paper "
"about your idea. It's especially frustrating when the work is concurrent,"
" which happens from time to time! But don't let that deter you---and "
"definitely don't let it motivate you to plant flags with not-quite-"
"finished research and over-claim the merits of the partial work. Do good "
"research and finish out your projects with complete and thorough "
"investigations, because that's what counts, and by far what matters most "
"in the long run."
msgstr ""
"**避免重新發明輪子。** 當你想出一個好想法並想要開始測試時，那很棒！但當你"
"還在早期階段時，盡可能徹底地確認它還沒有被做過。在專案進行到一半時才發現"
"已經有一篇關於你想法的論文，這會相當令人沮喪。當工作是同時進行的時候更加"
"令人沮喪，這種情況時有發生！但不要讓這些阻止你——更不要讓它驅使你用"
"不太完整的研究搶先佔位並過度聲稱部分工作的優點。做好研究，以完整和徹底的"
"調查完成你的專案，因為這才是重要的，而且從長遠來看這才是最關鍵的。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:77
msgid "Doing Rigorous Research in RL"
msgstr "在 RL 中進行嚴謹的研究"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:79
msgid ""
"Now you've come up with an idea, and you're fairly certain it hasn't been"
" done. You use the skills you've developed to implement it and you start "
"testing it out on standard domains. It looks like it works! But what does"
" that mean, and how well does it have to work to be important? This is "
"one of the hardest parts of research in deep RL. In order to validate "
"that your proposal is a meaningful contribution, you have to rigorously "
"prove that it actually gets a performance benefit over the strongest "
"possible baseline algorithm---whatever currently achieves SOTA (state of "
"the art) on your test domains. If you've invented a new test domain, so "
"there's no previous SOTA, you still need to try out whatever the most "
"reliable algorithm in the literature is that could plausibly do well in "
"the new test domain, and then you have to beat that."
msgstr ""
"現在你已經想出了一個想法，而且你相當確定它還沒有被做過。你利用已經培養的"
"技能來實作它，並開始在標準領域上測試。看起來有效！但這意味著什麼，它需要"
"多好才算重要？這是深度 RL 研究中最困難的部分之一。為了驗證你的提案是有意義"
"的貢獻，你必須嚴格證明它確實比最強大的可能基線演算法——無論目前在你的測試"
"領域上達到 SOTA（最先進水準，State of the Art）的是什麼——獲得了效能提升。"
"如果你發明了一個新的測試領域，所以沒有先前的 SOTA，你仍然需要嘗試文獻中"
"任何最可靠的、有可能在新測試領域中表現良好的演算法，然後你必須超越它。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:81
msgid ""
"**Set up fair comparisons.** If you implement your baseline from scratch"
"---as opposed to comparing against another paper's numbers directly---"
"it's important to spend as much time tuning your baseline as you spend "
"tuning your own algorithm. This will make sure that comparisons are fair."
" Also, do your best to hold \"all else equal\" even if there are "
"substantial differences between your algorithm and the baseline. For "
"example, if you're investigating architecture variants, keep the number "
"of model parameters approximately equal between your model and the "
"baseline. Under no circumstances handicap the baseline! It turns out that"
" the baselines in RL are pretty strong, and getting big, consistent wins "
"over them can be tricky or require some good insight in algorithm design."
msgstr ""
"**建立公平的比較。** 如果你從頭實作你的基線——而不是直接與其他論文的數字"
"比較——花在調整基線上的時間和花在調整你自己演算法上的時間一樣多是很重要的。"
"這將確保比較是公平的。另外，盡量保持「其他條件相同」，即使你的演算法和"
"基線之間存在重大差異。例如，如果你在研究架構變體，讓你的模型和基線的"
"模型參數數量大致相等。絕對不要給基線設置不利條件！事實證明，RL 中的基線"
"相當強大，要獲得相對於它們的大幅、一致的優勢可能很棘手，或者需要在演算法"
"設計上有好的洞察。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:83
msgid ""
"**Remove stochasticity as a confounder.** Beware of random seeds making "
"things look stronger or weaker than they really are, so run everything "
"for many random seeds (at least 3, but if you want to be thorough, do 10 "
"or more). This is really important and deserves a lot of emphasis: deep "
"RL seems fairly brittle with respect to random seed in a lot of common "
"use cases. There's potentially enough variance that two different groups "
"of random seeds can yield learning curves with differences so significant"
" that they look like they don't come from the same distribution at all "
"(see `figure 10 here`_)."
msgstr ""
"**消除隨機性作為混淆因子。** 注意隨機種子 (Random Seed) 讓結果看起來比實際"
"更強或更弱，所以要用很多隨機種子運行一切（至少 3 個，但如果你想更徹底，"
"做 10 個或更多）。這一點非常重要，值得大力強調：深度 RL 在許多常見使用案例"
"中對隨機種子相當敏感。潛在地有足夠的變異性，以至於兩組不同的隨機種子可能"
"產生差異顯著到看起來完全不像來自同一分佈的學習曲線"
"（見 `figure 10 here`_）。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:85
msgid ""
"**Run high-integrity experiments.** Don't just take the results from the "
"best or most interesting runs to use in your paper. Instead, launch new, "
"final experiments---for all of the methods that you intend to compare (if"
" you are comparing against your own baseline implementations)---and "
"precommit to report on whatever comes out of that. This is to enforce a "
"weak form of `preregistration`_: you use the tuning stage to come up with"
" your hypotheses, and you use the final runs to come up with your "
"conclusions."
msgstr ""
"**進行高誠信度的實驗。** 不要只取最好或最有趣的運行結果放在你的論文中。"
"相反，啟動新的、最終的實驗——對你打算比較的所有方法（如果你是與自己的基線"
"實作比較的話）——並預先承諾報告其結果。這是為了強制執行一種弱形式的 "
"`preregistration`_：你用調整階段來提出假設，用最終運行來得出結論。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:87
msgid ""
"**Check each claim separately.** Another critical aspect of doing "
"research is to run an ablation analysis. Any method you propose is likely"
" to have several key design decisions---like architecture choices or "
"regularization techniques, for instance---each of which could separately "
"impact performance. The claim you'll make in your work is that those "
"design decisions collectively help, but this is really a bundle of "
"several claims in disguise: one for each such design element. By "
"systematically evaluating what would happen if you were to swap them out "
"with alternate design choices, or remove them entirely, you can figure "
"out how to correctly attribute credit for the benefits your method "
"confers. This lets you make each separate claim with a measure of "
"confidence, and increases the overall strength of your work."
msgstr ""
"**分別檢驗每個主張。** 做研究的另一個關鍵方面是進行消融分析。你提出的任何"
"方法可能都有幾個關鍵的設計決策——如架構選擇或正則化技術等——每一個都可能"
"單獨影響效能。你在工作中要提出的主張是這些設計決策整體上有所幫助，但這"
"實際上是幾個偽裝的主張的集合：每個設計元素各一個。透過系統性地評估如果"
"將它們替換為替代設計選擇或完全移除會發生什麼，你可以弄清楚如何正確歸因"
"你的方法所帶來的好處。這讓你能以一定的信心提出每個獨立的主張，並增強你"
"工作的整體力度。"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:90
msgid "Closing Thoughts"
msgstr "結語"

#: ../../spinningup/spinningup.rst:92
msgid ""
"Deep RL is an exciting, fast-moving field, and we need as many people as "
"possible to go through the open problems and make progress on them. "
"Hopefully, you feel a bit more prepared to be a part of it after reading "
"this! And whenever you're ready, `let us know`_."
msgstr ""
"深度 RL 是一個令人興奮、快速發展的領域，我們需要盡可能多的人來解決開放問題"
"並推動進展。希望在閱讀本文之後，你會覺得自己更有準備成為其中的一員！"
"而當你準備好的時候，`let us know`_。"

